t 1350","1436":"1436","1469":"1469","1369":"1369","1379":"1379","1377 ":"about 1377","1400":"1400","1345":"1345","1377":"1377","1355":"1355","1376":"1376","1321":"1321","1375":"1375","1430":"1430","1353":"1353","after 1375":"after 1375","1329":"1329","Pott Shrigley, Cheshire, England":"Pott Shrigley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Norbury, Derbyshire, England":"Norbury, Derbyshire, England","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Pott Shrigley,Cheshire, England":"Pott Shrigley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Downes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Shropshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Down   with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish (counties Clare and Limerick): shortened Anglicized form of Irish Gaelic <b>Ó Dubháin</b> (see   Doane  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Down","meanings":["English (Devon): topographic name for someone who lived on or near a down or low hill, from Middle English <i>dun(e)</i>, <i>doun(e)</i> (Old English <i>dūn</i>) ‘down, low hill’. See also   Downer  .","English (Devon): possibly in some cases a patronymic from the Old English personal name <i>Dūn</i>, but later names of this origin cannot reliably be distinguished from those originating from the topographic sense. See   Dunn   2."]},{"name":"Downs","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Downes  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Downes was born in 1351, in Pott Shrigley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Downes II, was 31 and his mother, Margery Trussell, was 23. He married Alice Prestbury in 1376, in Pott Shrigley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1385, in his hometown, at the age of 34."},"et":{"1351–1385":"1351–1385","1353–Female":"1353–Surnud","1355–Female":"1355–Surnud","1345–1400":"1345–1400","1369–1469":"1369–1469","1377–1436":"1377–1436","1379–1430":"1379–1430","1321–1375":"1321–1375","1329–Female":"1329–Surnud","1385":"1385","1351":"1351","Abt 1379":"umbes 1379","Abt 1350":"umbes 1350","1436":"1436","1469":"1469","1369":"1369","1379":"1379","1377 ":"umbes 1377","1400":"1400","1345":"1345","1377":"1377","1355":"1355","1376":"1376","1321":"1321","1375":"1375","1430":"1430","1353":"1353","after 1375":"pärast 1375","1329":"1329","Pott Shrigley, Cheshire, England":"Pott Shrigley, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norbury, Derbyshire, England":"Norbury, Derbyshire, England","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Pott Shrigley,Cheshire, England":"Pott Shrigley, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1351–1385":"1351–1385","1353–Female":"1353–Kuollut","1355–Female":"1355–Kuollut","1345–1400":"1345–1400","1369–14